         "lines":[
             {"d":"ltr", "words":[{"w":"And a feminine noun is referred to by the pronoun هِيَ whether it denotes a human being, an animal or a thing. e.g."}]},
             {"words":[{"w":"أَيْنَ آمِنَةُ؟"}]},
             {"d":"ltr","words":[{"w":"Where is Aminah?"}]},
             {"words":[{"w":"هِيَ فِي البَيْتِ."}]},
             {"d":"ltr","words":[{"w":"She is in the house."}]},
             {"words":[{"w":"أَيْنَ السَّعَةُ؟"}]},
             {"d":"ltr","words":[{"w":"Where is the watch?"}]},
             {"words":[{"w":"هِيَ عَلَي السَّرِيرِ."}]},
             {"d":"ltr","words":[{"w":"It is on the bed"}]},
             {"d":"ltr","words":[{"w":"\nMost feminine nouns end with a round ta (ة) but there are some which do not have any ending."}]}
         ]   
        },
        {   "d":"ltr",
            "mode":"lesson", "height":50.0,
            "words":[{"w":"Note:"}]
        },
        {"mode":"card",
            "lines":[
                {"d":"ltr", "words":[{"w":"a. We have learn that the tanwin is the indefinite article, e.g. بَيْتٌ a house. The rule does not apply to proper nouns. So حَامِدٌ is just \"hamid\", not \"a hamid\".\n\n2. Feminine proper nouns have no tanwin, e.g. فَاطِمَةُ،  زَزْنَبُ،  آمِنَةُ "}]}               
            ]   
        },
